# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: influxdb
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:influxdb/database-engine] A **database engine** (or **storage engine**) is the underlying software component that a database management system (DBMS) uses to create, read, update and delete (CRUD) data from a database.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] Most database management systems include their own application programming interface (API) that allows the user to interact with their underlying engine without going through the user interface of the DBMS.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] The term "database engine" is frequently used interchangeably with "database server" or "database management system".
[src:influxdb/database-engine] A "database instance" refers to the processes and memory structures of the running database engine.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] Many of the modern DBMS support multiple storage engines within the same database.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] For example, MySQL supports InnoDB as well as MyISAM.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] Information in a database is stored in the form of bits, laid out into data structures on storage hardware.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] These data structures are designed for efficient reads and writes to and from the storage hardware.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] Typically the storage hardware itself is designed to meet the requirements of various systems, including databases, that extensively utilize storage.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] An operating DBMS always utilizes several storage types simultaneously.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] These different storage types, such as flash memory and external disk storage, each require different data layout methods.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] In principle, database storage can be viewed as a linear address space where every bit of data has a unique address.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] In practice, only a very small percentage of addresses are kept as initial reference points, which also require storage.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] Most data is accessed instead by indirection using displacement calculations (distance in bits from the reference points) and data structures which define access paths (using pointers) to all needed data in an effective manner, optimized for the needed data access operations.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] A database, while in operation, resides simultaneously in several types of storage, forming a storage hierarchy.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] Inside of a contemporary computer hosting a DBMS, most of the "database" part resides, partially replicated, in volatile storage.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] Data that are actively being processed and manipulated reside inside the processor, possibly in processor's caches.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] These data are read from and written to memory, typically through a computer bus, which is usually a volatile storage component.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] Computer memory communicates data to and from external storage, typically through standard storage interfaces or networks (e.g., fibre channel, iSCSI).
[src:influxdb/database-engine] A storage array, a common external storage unit, typically has storage hierarchy of its own.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] A fast cache, typically consisting of volatile and fast DRAM, is connected (via standard interfaces) to drives.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] These drives may have different speeds, like flash drives and non-volatile magnetic disk drives.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] Speed and price are generally correlated.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] The drives may be connected to magnetic tapes, on which the least active parts of a large database may reside.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] This may also be where backups are located.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] A data structure is an abstract construct that embeds data in a well defined manner.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] An efficient data structure allows manipulation of the data in efficient ways.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] The data manipulation may include data insertion, deletion, updating and retrieval in various modes.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] A certain data structure type may be very effective in certain operations, and very ineffective in others.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] A data structure type is selected upon DBMS development to best meet the operations needed for the types of data it contains.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] Type of data structure selected for a certain task typically also takes into consideration the type of storage it resides in (e.g., speed of access, minimal size of storage chunk accessed, etc.).
[src:influxdb/database-engine] In some DBMSs database administrators have the flexibility to select among options of data structures to contain user data for performance reasons.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] Sometimes the data structures have selectable parameters to tune the database performance.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] Databases may store data in many data structure types.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] In contrast to conventional row-orientation, relational databases can also be column-oriented or correlational in the way they store data in any particular structure.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] In general, substantial performance improvement is gained if different types of database objects that are usually utilized together are laid in storage in proximity, being "clustered".
[src:influxdb/database-engine] This usually allows to retrieve needed related objects from storage in minimum number of input operations (each sometimes substantially time-consuming).
[src:influxdb/database-engine] Even for in-memory databases clustering provides performance advantage due to common utilization of large caches for input-output operations in memory, with similar resulting behavior.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] For example, it may be beneficial to cluster a record of an "item" in stock with all its respective "order" records.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] The decision of whether to cluster certain objects or not depends on the objects' utilization statistics, object sizes, caches sizes, storage types, etc.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] Indexing is a technique some storage engines use for improving database performance.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] The many types of indexes share the common property that they reduce the need to examine every entry when running a query.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] In large databases, this can reduce query time/cost by orders of magnitude.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] The simplest form of index is a sorted list of values that can be searched using a binary search with an adjacent reference to the location of the entry, analogous to the index in the back of a book.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] The same data can have multiple indexes (an employee database could be indexed by last name and hire date).
[src:influxdb/database-engine] Indexes affect performance, but not results.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] Database designers can add or remove indexes without changing application logic, reducing maintenance costs as the database grows and database usage evolves.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] Indexes can speed up data access, but they consume space in the database, and must be updated each time the data is altered.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] Indexes therefore can speed data access but slow data maintenance.
[src:influxdb/database-engine] These two properties determine whether a given index is worth the cost.
[src:influxdb/influxdb-v2] Write data to InfluxDB using a number of different options.
[src:influxdb/influxdb-v2] Use Flux to query and transform your data.
[src:influxdb/influxdb-v2] Use InfluxDB tasks to process and downsample data.
[src:influxdb/influxdb-v2] Build powerful dashboards to visualize your data.
[src:influxdb/influxdb-v2] Monitor metrics and send alerts with InfluxDB.
[src:influxdb/influxdb-v2] Customize your **InfluxDB OSS URL** and we’ll update code examples for you.
[src:influxdb/influxdb-v2] For more information, see InfluxDB OSS URLs.
[src:influxdb/influxdb-v2] Stronger token security in **InfluxDB OSS 2.9.0** — tokens are hashed on disk by default.
[src:influxdb/influxdb-v2] Existing tokens are hashed on first startup and can’t be recovered afterward.
[src:influxdb/influxdb-v2] Hashed tokens authenticate exactly like unhashed tokens — clients and integrations keep working.
[src:influxdb/influxdb-v2] Explorer 1.9 is now available with InfluxQL support, an AI-assisted Flux to SQL converter (beta), and new live sample data simulators.
[src:influxdb/influxdb-v2] Explorer 1.9 includes new features and improvements that make it easier to query, visualize, and manage data.
[src:influxdb/influxdb-v2] InfluxDB 3 Core 3.10 adds an automatic catalog format upgrade, a configurable query-concurrency limit, and processing engine improvements.
[src:influxdb/influxdb-v2] For more information, see the InfluxDB 3 Core release notes.
[src:influxdb/influxdb-v2] InfluxDB 3 Enterprise 3.10 adds automated backup and restore, row-level deletions, and user management, with an automatic catalog format upgrade and performance preview improvements.
[src:influxdb/influxdb-v2] Backup and restore, row-level deletions, and the performance preview require the Enterprise storage engine upgrade (opt-in beta).
[src:influxdb/influxdb-v2] Telegraf Enterprise combines Telegraf Controller, a centralized management console for Telegraf, with official support from InfluxData.
[src:influxdb/influxdb-v2] Manage configurations, monitor fleet health, and operate tens of thousands of Telegraf agents from a single system.
[src:influxdb/influxdb-v2] tag for InfluxDB Docker images will point to InfluxDB 3 Core.
[src:influxdb/influxdb-v2] To avoid unexpected upgrades, use specific version tags in your Docker deployments.
[src:influxdb/influxdb-v2] If using Docker to install and run InfluxDB, the `latest` tag will point to InfluxDB 3 Core.
[src:influxdb/influxdb] The latest version of InfluxDB, 3.x, is written in the Rust programming language.
[src:influxdb/influxdb] Y Combinator-backed company Errplane began developing InfluxDB as an open-source project in late 2013 for performance monitoring and alerting.
[src:influxdb/influxdb] Errplane raised an $8.1M Series A financing led by Mayfield Fund and Trinity Ventures in November 2014.
[src:influxdb/influxdb] In late 2015, Errplane officially changed its name to InfluxData Inc.
[src:influxdb/influxdb] InfluxData raised Series B round of funding of $16 million in September 2016.
[src:influxdb/influxdb] In February 2018, InfluxData closed a $35 million Series C round of funding led by Sapphire Ventures.
[src:influxdb/influxdb] Another round of $60 million was disclosed in 2019.
[src:influxdb/influxdb] In February 2023, another $81 million was closed in a Series E round.
[src:influxdb/influxdb] InfluxDB provides an SQL-like language with built-in time-centric functions for querying a data structure composed of measurements, series, and points.
[src:influxdb/influxdb] Each point consists of several key-value pairs called the fieldset and a timestamp.
[src:influxdb/influxdb] When grouped together by a set of key-value pairs called the tagset, these define a series.
[src:influxdb/influxdb] Finally, series are grouped together by a string identifier to form a measurement.
[src:influxdb/influxdb] Values can be 64-bit integers, 64-bit floating points, strings, and booleans.
[src:influxdb/influxdb] Points are indexed by their time and tagset.
[src:influxdb/influxdb] Retention policies are defined on a measurement and control how data is downsampled and deleted.
[src:influxdb/influxdb] Continuous Queries run periodically, storing results in a target measurement.
[src:influxdb/influxdb] InfluxData regularly hosts events related to InfluxDB called InfluxDays.
[src:influxdb/influxdb] The InfluxDays are technical conventions focused on the evolution of InfluxDB on technical and business points of view.
[src:influxdb/influxdb] Those events take place once a year in three locations: New York, San Francisco or London.
[src:influxdb/influxdb] The InfluxDays cover a wide variety of different subjects: software engineering and coding talks as well as business-focused and practical workshops.
[src:influxdb/influxdb] Companies can showcase how they use InfluxDB.
[src:influxdb/influxdb] InfluxDB accepts data via HTTP, TCP, and UDP.
[src:influxdb/influxdb] measurement(,tag_key=tag_val)* field_key=field_val(,field_key_n=field_value_n)* (nanoseconds-timestamp)?
[src:influxdb/influxdb] Contributors to InfluxDB need to give InfluxData Inc. the right to license the contributions and the rest of the software in any way, including under a closed-source license.
[src:influxdb/influxdb] The Contributor License Agreement claims not to be a copyright transfer agreement.
[src:influxdb/influxdb] In May 2016, InfluxData announced that the computer cluster component of InfluxDB would be sold as closed-source software in order to create a sustainable source of funding for the project's development.
[src:influxdb/influxdb] Community reaction was mixed, with some feeling the move was a "bait and switch".
[src:influxdb/influxdb] InfluxDB 3 Core is InfluxData's newest open source product and is intentionally designed to be an “edge data collector”, not a replacement for InfluxDB OSS v1 and v2.
[src:influxdb/influxdb] InfluxDB 3 Core has a 5 database limit and does not include a data compactor for fast historical querying.
[src:influxdb/influxdb] In addition to InfluxDB 3 Core, InfluxDB 3 Enterprise is the commercial version of the open source core project.
[src:influxdb/influxdb] Purchasing a software license for InfluxDB 3 Enterprise is required to replace InfluxDB OSS v1 and v2 functionality in a commercial setting, though a free version of InfluxDB 3 Enterprise is available for hobbyist and home use.
[src:influxdb/key-concepts] This page documents an earlier version of InfluxDB OSS.
[src:influxdb/key-concepts] InfluxDB 3 Core is the latest stable version.
[src:influxdb/key-concepts] Stronger token security: tokens are stored as hashes on disk, so a copy of the database file doesn’t expose usable tokens.
[src:influxdb/key-concepts] Existing tokens are hashed on first startup and the original strings can’t be recovered afterward — **capture any plaintext tokens you still need before you upgrade**.
[src:influxdb/key-concepts] For more information, see Token hashing.
[src:influxdb/key-concepts] Before working with InfluxDB 2.9, it’s helpful to learn a few key concepts.
[src:influxdb/key-concepts] Browse the topics and videos below to learn more.
[src:influxdb/key-concepts] InfluxDB structures data using elements such as timestamps, field keys, field values, tags, etc.
[src:influxdb/key-concepts] InfluxDB uses a tabular data schema for displaying raw data in Data Explorer and for returning query results in annotated CSV syntax.
[src:influxdb/key-concepts] Principles and tradeoffs related to InfluxDB design.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] This document outlines the internal workings of the storage engine.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] This information is presented both as a reference and to aid those looking to maximize performance.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] The storage engine handles data from the point an API write request is received through writing data to the physical disk.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] Data is written to InfluxDB using line protocol sent via HTTP POST request to the `/api/v2/write` endpoint or the `/write` 1.x compatibility endpoint.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] Batches of points are sent to InfluxDB, compressed, and written to a WAL for immediate durability.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] Points are also written to an in-memory cache and become immediately queryable.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] The in-memory cache is periodically written to disk in the form of TSM files.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] As TSM files accumulate, the storage engine combines and compacts accumulated them into higher level TSM files.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] While points can be sent individually, for efficiency, most applications send points in batches.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] Points in a POST body can be from an arbitrary number of series, measurements, and tag sets.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] Points in a batch do not have to be from the same measurement or tagset.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] The **Write Ahead Log** (WAL) retains InfluxDB data when the storage engine restarts.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] The WAL ensures data is durable in case of an unexpected failure.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] Data is written to disk using `fsync()`.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] When data is successfully written to disk, a response confirms the write request was successful.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] `fsync()` takes the file and pushes pending writes all the way to the disk.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] As a system call, `fsync()` has a kernel context switch that’s computationally expensive, but guarantees that data is safe on disk.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] When the storage engine restarts, the WAL file is read back into the in-memory database.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] InfluxDB then answers requests to the `/read` endpoint.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] The **cache** is an in-memory copy of data points currently stored in the WAL.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] The WAL and cache are separate entities and do not interact with each other.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] The storage engine coordinates writes to both.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] Cache snapshots are cache objects currently being written to TSM files.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] They’re kept in memory while flushing so they can be queried along with the cache.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] Queries to the storage engine merge data from the cache with data from the TSM files.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] Queries execute on a copy of the data that is made from the cache at query processing time.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] This way writes that come in while a query is running do not affect the result.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] Deletes sent to the cache clear the specified key or time range for a specified key.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] To efficiently compact and store data, the storage engine groups field values by series key, and then orders those field values by time.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] The storage engine uses a **Time-Structured Merge Tree** (TSM) data format.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] TSM files store compressed series data in a columnar format.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] To improve efficiency, the storage engine only stores differences (or *deltas*) between values in a series.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] Column-oriented storage lets the engine read by series key and omit extraneous data.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] After fields are stored safely in TSM files, the WAL is truncated and the cache is cleared.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] The **compaction** process creates read-optimized TSM files.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] The TSM compaction code is quite complex.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] However, the high-level goal is quite simple: organize values for a series together into long runs to best optimize compression and scanning queries.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] As data cardinality (the number of series) grows, queries read more series keys and become slower.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] The **Time Series Index** ensures queries remain fast as data cardinality grows.
[src:influxdb/storage-engine] The TSI stores series keys grouped by measurement, tag, and field.
[src:influxdb/time-series-database] A **time series database** is a software system that is optimized for storing and serving time series through associated pairs of time(s) and value(s).
[src:influxdb/time-series-database] In some fields, *time series* may be called profiles, curves, traces or trends.
[src:influxdb/time-series-database] Several early time series databases are associated with industrial applications which could efficiently store measured values from sensory equipment (also referred to as data historians), but now are used in support of a much wider range of applications.
[src:influxdb/time-series-database] In many cases, the repositories of time-series data will utilize compression algorithms to manage the data efficiently.
[src:influxdb/time-series-database] Although it is possible to store time-series data in many different database types, the design of these systems with time as a key index is distinctly different from relational databases which reduce discrete relationships through referential models.
[src:influxdb/time-series-database] Time series datasets are relatively large and uniform compared to other datasets―usually being composed of a timestamp and associated data.
[src:influxdb/time-series-database] Time series datasets can also have fewer relationships between data entries in different tables and don't require indefinite storage of entries.
[src:influxdb/time-series-database] The unique properties of time series datasets mean that time series databases can provide significant improvements in storage space and performance over general purpose databases.
[src:influxdb/time-series-database] For instance, due to the uniformity of time series data, specialized compression algorithms can provide improvements over regular compression algorithms designed to work on less uniform data.
[src:influxdb/time-series-database] Time series databases can also be configured to regularly delete (or downsample) old data, unlike regular databases which are designed to store data indefinitely.
[src:influxdb/time-series-database] Special database indices can also provide boosts in query performance.
[src:influxdb/time-series-database] Time series databases are commonly designed for append-heavy workloads, where large numbers of measurements or events are continuously written together with timestamps.
[src:influxdb/time-series-database] Specialized time series management systems have been developed for data from monitoring, automation, the Internet of Things, and cyber-physical systems, where data may be produced at high velocity and in large volumes.
[src:influxdb/time-series-database] Common design goals include high-throughput data ingestion, low-latency queries over time ranges, efficient compression, and support for aggregation or downsampling over time windows.
[src:influxdb/time-series-database] Many systems also organize data by tags, devices, sensors, or other metadata, so that users can retrieve measurements by both time range and source.
[src:influxdb/time-series-database] Time series databases are used in application areas where data is collected continuously over time.
[src:influxdb/time-series-database] Examples include industrial monitoring, operational historians, infrastructure and application monitoring, Internet of Things sensor data, energy systems, financial market data, and scientific measurements.
[src:influxdb/time-series-database] In monitoring applications, time series database systems may need to process large amounts of sensor or metric data in real time, execute continuous queries, and support analytical tasks such as data exploration, anomaly detection, predictive modeling, trend analysis, and missing-value recovery.
[src:influxdb/time-series-database] Time series databases are often used as storage and query systems for downstream analytical tasks, including forecasting, anomaly detection, imputation, and pattern matching.
[src:influxdb/time-series-database] Some systems also integrate analytical or machine-learning functions closer to the database layer, allowing users to invoke forecasting or anomaly detection through database query interfaces such as SQL.
[src:influxdb/time-series-database] Recent research in time series analysis has also explored large pre-trained models for tasks such as forecasting, imputation, and anomaly detection.
[src:influxdb/time-series-database] These models are usually discussed as analytical methods for time series data rather than as defining features of time series databases.
[src:influxdb/time-series-database] The following database systems have functionality optimized for handling time series data.
